30. (9) Mute and. Liquid. When a vowel naturally short precedes a Mute and Liquid, the syllable is never lengthened by ‘position' by the Republican Dramatists as it is in other poetry. While Ennius in his Epic and Lucilius in his Satires allow thern- selves such scansions as myrum, febris, fibras, triclini, the Drama- tists recognize only myrum, triclini, &e The syllables were apparently short in the ordinary every-day utterance of their time, just as in Greek¹3 so that umorum, febris, &a represent the colloquial pro- nunciation‚ while myrum, febris belong to the artificia] language of poetry. That this distinction holds even for the fourth century ΑΒ.2 we see from the remark of Servius on perciyro in Virg. Aen. i. 384: ‘per-' habet accentum...Muta enim et liquida quotiens ponuntur metrum iuvant, non accentum.
